==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glyph
<hw>Glyph</hw> <pr>(gl⟦icr⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>glyfh`</grk> carving, fr. <grk>gly`fein</grk> to carve: cf. F.
<ets>glyphe</ets>. Cf. <er>Cleave</er> to split.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A sunken channel or groove, usually vertical.
See <er>Triglyph</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch⟦ae⟧ol.)</fld> <def>A carved figure or
character, incised or in relief; a carved pictograph; hence, a
pictograph representing a form originally adopted for sculpture, whether
carved or painted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glyphic</ent>⟦br⟧
